## **Abstract**

Artificial intelligence (AI) models for basal cell carcinoma (BCC) detection have predominantly relied on single-modality inputs, limiting both clinical applicability and interpretability. To address these challenges, we propose a tri-modal deep learning ensemble that integrates dermoscopic images, clinical photographs, and structured patient metadata for robust and interpretable BCC classification. Our framework combines three specialized branches: (1) an ensemble of convolutional neural networks (CNNs) for dermoscopy, (2) a domain-adapted CNN for clinical photographs, and (3) a multilayer perceptron for metadata (age, sex, lesion site). Outputs from each branch are fused at the logit level using optimized weights, and classification thresholds are systematically tuned to balance sensitivity and specificity. We evaluate the system on three datasets—HAM10000, PAD-UFES-20, and a private paired cohort—showing that the tri-modal ensemble achieved AUROC 0.9992 and accuracy 99.02\%, with F1-score 0.99, exceeding unimodal and bi-modal approaches. Interpretability is embedded throughout: Grad-CAM highlights salient image regions, SHAP quantifies metadata contributions, and both are validated via blinded dermatologist review, achieving >80\% concordance with clinical features. This integrated, explainable approach helps address the gap between algorithmic accuracy and clinical trust, supporting deployment in teledermatology and resource-limited screening environments. Our results underscore the value of multimodal, clinician-validated AI systems for advancing real-world skin cancer diagnostics.

